The graph of $r = \cos 2 \theta \sec \theta$ is shown below.

[asy]
import TrigMacros;

size(400);

real g(real x)
{
	return cos(2*x)*sec(x);
}

draw(graph(g,-3*pi,3*pi,n=700,join=operator ..),red);
trig_axes(-3*pi,3*pi+.2,-2,2,pi,1);
layer();
rm_trig_labels(-5, 5, 2);
[/asy]

The graph has a vertical asymptote at $\theta = \pi,$ because $\sec \theta$ is not defined at $\theta = \pi.$  The equation of the vertical asymptote is $\boxed{r = 0}.$ The answer is: r = 0

[asy]
pair P,Q,R;
P = (0,0);
Q = (10,0);
R = (0,12);
draw(P--Q--R--P);
draw(rightanglemark(Q,P,R,25));
label("$P$",P,SW);
label("$Q$",Q,SE);
label("$R$",R,N);
label("$20$",(Q+R)/2,NE);
[/asy]

Since $\triangle PQR$ is a right triangle, we have $\tan R = \frac{PQ}{PR}$.  Also, $\sin R = \frac{PQ}{PR}$.  Thus, $\tan R = 4\sin R$ gives us $\frac{PQ}{PR} = 4\cdot \frac{PQ}{PR}$.  This simplifies to $PQ = 4PR$, so $PR = \frac{1}{4}PQ = \frac{1}{4}(20) = \boxed{5}$. The answer is: 5

