Let $AB = x,$ $BC = y,$ and $AC = z.$  We have $x + y + z = 2007.$  We want to minimize $y - x,$ subject to $x,$ $y,$ and $z$ being positive integers and $y \ge x.$  We can write
\[2007 = x + y + z = x + (x + 1) + (x + 2) = 3x + 3.\]Then $x = 676.$  We want $y$ to be as close to $x$ as possible, so $y = x + 1 = 677.$  Then $z = 2007 - x - y = 679.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, B, C;

A = (0,0);
B = (10,0);
C = (10,12);

draw(A--B--C--cycle);
draw(B--(B + 1,0));

label("$A$", A, SW);
label("$B$", B, S);
label("$C$", C, N);
label("$x$", (B + (B + 1,0))/2, E);
label("$y$", (B + C)/2, NE);
label("$z$", (C + (A,12))/2, W);
[/asy]

Hence, the minimum value of $y - x$ is $677 - 676 = \boxed{1}.$ The answer is: 1

